## Example 5

Simplify $\quad \frac{5}{7} \cdot \frac{2}{3}=\frac{5}{7} \times \frac{3}{2} \quad$ (when changing from division to multiplication invert)

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{15}{14} \\
& =1 \frac{1}{14}
\end{aligned}
$$

## Other Bases
The same applies to numbers in other bases
For example base five system is based on powers of five $5^{2} 5^{1} 5^{0}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 234=2 \times 5^{2}+3 \times 5^{1}+4 \times 5^{0} \\
& \text { (but } 5^{0}=\text { 1twenty, } 3 \\
& \text { fives, } 4 \text { units }
\end{aligned}
$$

Base two is based on power two

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 2^{2} 2^{1} 2^{0} \\
& 110=1 \times 2^{2}+1 \times 2^{1}+0 \times 2^{0}\left(\text { but } 2^{0}=1\right. \\
& \text { two } 1 \text { fours, } 1 \text { twos, } 0 \text { units }
\end{aligned}
$$

Take note that all digits forming base five are less than five e.g. 234, also all digits forming a number in base two are less than two e.g $1011_{2}$
The notation $234_{\text {five }}$ means 234 in base five, also $1001_{2}$ mean 1011 in base two.

## Example 3

Find the value of the following giving the answer in standard form.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 3,43 \times 10^{3}+5,27 \times 10^{4}=3430+52700 \\
& =56130 \\
& =5,613 \times 10^{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Or by factorization

$$
\begin{aligned}
3,43 \times 10^{3}+5,27 \times 10^{4} & = & 10^{3}(3,43+5,27 \times 10) \\
& = & 10^{3}(3,43+52,7) \\
& = & 10^{3}(56,13) \\
& = & 10^{3} \times 56,13) \\
& = & 10^{3} \times 5,613 \times 10^{1}\left(56,13=5,613 \times 10^{1}\right) \\
& = & 5,613 \times 10^{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

b) By changing to ordinary form

$$
\begin{aligned}
3,7 \times 10^{-3}-5,2 \times 10^{-4} & =\frac{3,7}{10^{3}}-\frac{5,2}{10^{4}} \\
& =0,0037-0,00052 \\
& =0,00318 \\
& =3,18 \times 10^{-3}
\end{aligned}
$$
Or by factorisation

$$
\begin{array}{rlrl}
3,7 \times 10^{-2}-5,2 \times 10^{-4} & = & 10^{-3}\left(3,7-5,2 \times 10^{-1}\right) \\
& = & 10^{-3}\left(3,7-5,2 \times 10^{-1}\right) \\
& = & 10^{-3}(3,18) \\
& = & 3,18 \times 10^{-3}
\end{array}
$$

Example 7

Find the value of $\frac{4}{225}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{4}{225} & =4 \times \frac{1}{225} \quad \text { (but } \frac{1}{2,25} \text {, is the reciprocal of } 2,25 \\
& =4 \times 0,4444 \\
& =1,778 \text { to } 4 \mathrm{~s} . \mathrm{f}
\end{aligned}
$$

