# Joint variation 

Occurs when one variable depends on a combination of other variables linked by a multiplication sign. For example the volume of cylinder is $\mathrm{v}=\pi \mathrm{r}^{2} \mathrm{~h}$. The formula shows that the volume of a cylinder depends on the radius and the height. The volume varies as the height and the square of the radius (r)

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{V}=\mathrm{r}^{2} \mathrm{~h} \\
& \mathrm{~V}=\mathrm{kr}^{2} \mathrm{~h}
\end{aligned}
$$

## Example 5

If $Z$ varies directly as $x$ and inversely as $y, z=71 / 2$ when $x=3$ and $y=5$
i) Find relationship between $x, y$ and $z$
ii) Find $Z$ when $x=1 / 3$ and $y=41 / 2$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& z=1 / y \\
& z=\frac{k x}{y} \\
& 7 \frac{1}{2}=\frac{3}{5} k \\
& \frac{15}{2}=\frac{3 k}{5}
\end{aligned}
$$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 6 k=75 \\
& k=\frac{75}{6} \\
& k=\frac{25}{2} \\
& z=\frac{25 x}{2 y}
\end{aligned}
$$

ii) When $x=\frac{14}{5}$ and $y=4 \frac{1}{2}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& z=\frac{25 x}{y} \\
& =25 \frac{\left(\frac{14}{5}\right)}{4 \frac{1}{2}} \\
& =\frac{70}{\frac{9}{2}} \\
& z=\frac{140}{9}
\end{aligned}
$$

# Example 2 

A map of Bulawayo is drawn to a scale of 1:50 000. On the map the Trade Fair covers on area of $8 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}$. Find the true area of the Trade Fair in hectares ( $1 \mathrm{ha}=10000 \mathrm{~m}^{2}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Scale factor } & =\frac{50000}{1} \\
& =(50000)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Area factor } & =(50000)^{2} \\
& =2500000000
\end{aligned}
$$

Area of Trade Fair $=\frac{2500000000 \times 8}{10000 \times 10000}$

$$
=200 \text { hectares }
$$

## Example 4

The cylindrical containers of maize meal are similar and contain 27 kg and 125 kg of maize meal respectively. If the radius of the bigger container is 25 cm , find the radius of the smaller one.

Volume ratio $\quad=$ Mass ratio
$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{125}{127} \\
& =\left({ }^{5} / 3\right)^{3} \\
& \text { Scale factor }=\frac{5}{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Radius of smaller cylinder $=25 \div \frac{5}{3}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =25 \times 3 / 5 \\
& =15 \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

## THE FORMULA FOR SOLVING QUADRATIC EQUATIONS

The general form of a quadratic equation is a $x^{2}+b x+c=0$. The roots of this are found by complete the square, a $x^{2}+\mathrm{b} x+\mathrm{c}=0$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& x^{2}+\frac{b}{a} x+\frac{c}{a}=0 \\
& x^{2}+\frac{b}{a} x=\frac{-c}{a} \\
& x^{2}+\frac{b x}{a}+\left(\frac{b}{2 a}\right)^{2}=\frac{-c}{a}+\left(\frac{b}{2 a}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(x+\frac{b}{2 a}\right)^{2}=\frac{b^{2}-4 a c}{4 a^{2}} \\
& x+\frac{b}{2 a}= \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^{2}-4 a c}{4 a^{2}}} \\
& x=-b \pm \sqrt{\frac{b^{2}-4 a c}{2 a}}
\end{aligned}
$$

## Example 2

Given $\mathrm{a}=\binom{3}{4}$ and $\mathrm{b}=\binom{-1}{-2}$ find
a) $\quad a+b$
b) $\quad a-b$
a) $\quad a+b=\binom{3}{4}+\binom{-1}{-2}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\quad\binom{3+-1}{4-+2} \\
& =\quad\binom{3-1}{4-2} \\
& =\quad\binom{2}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

b) $\quad a-b=\binom{3}{4}-\binom{-1}{2}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(\begin{array}{cc}
3- & -1 \\
4 & 2
\end{array}\right) \\
& =\binom{3+4}{4+2} \\
& =\binom{7}{6}
\end{aligned}
$$

