## Example 4

A sector $70^{\circ}$ is shaded on a circle of radius 3 cm . Calculate its area.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Area of a sector } & =\frac{\Theta \times \pi r^{2}}{360} \\
& =\frac{\Theta \times 3 \cdot 12 \times 3 \times 3}{360} \\
& =5,46 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

## Example 4

Find the volume of the diagram below. Given that its length is 9 m
Volume $=$ Cross sectional Area x height

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =1 / 3(5+7) 3 \times 9 \\
& =18 \times 9 \\
& =162 \mathrm{~cm}^{2}
\end{aligned} \quad \text { Cross section is a trapezium) }
$$

## Example 6

A trader make a $10 \%$ profit by selling a two plate stove $\$ 60$. What is the cost price of the stove

$$
\begin{aligned}
& 110 \%: \$ 60 \\
& 100 \%: \text { 1ess }
\end{aligned} \quad \text { use proportion }
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{100}{110} \times 60 \\
& =\frac{600}{11}
\end{aligned}
$$

# Example 1 

In a school, it is known that 20 students out of every 50 advanced level students, make it to university. Find
i) the probability of students who will go to university next year
ii) the probability of students who will not go to university
iii) The number of students who will go to university if 75 students sit for their advanced level examinations
i) $\quad \mathrm{P}$ (students going to university) $=\frac{\text { number of required }}{\text { number of possible outcome }}$

$$
=\frac{20}{50}
$$

$$
=\frac{2}{5}
$$

ii) $\quad P$ (Student not going to university) $=1-P$ (students who will go).

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =1-\frac{2}{5} \\
& =\frac{3}{5}
\end{aligned}
$$

iii) Number of students $=\mathrm{P}$ (students going to university) x 75 going to university.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{2}{5} \times 75 \\
& =\underline{30 \text { students }}
\end{aligned}
$$

